Class ParseConfiguration

  • java.lang.Object
    • es.ed0.tinyjson.parser.ParseConfiguration

  • public class ParseConfiguration
extends java.lang.Object
    Configuration object for JSONParser. Here some parsing setting and parameters can be set to allow a more custom parsing of jsons

      • setAllowArbitraryCommas

        public void setAllowArbitraryCommas(boolean key)
        Allow random commas at the end of json bodies. Example: ["value", 3, true,]

        Default: false

      • setFailOnDuplicateMappings

        public void setFailOnDuplicateMappings(boolean key)
        Parser will throw exception if a duplicate mapping was found

        Default: false

      • setAllowUnknownEscapes

        public void setAllowUnknownEscapes(boolean key)
        Allow unknown escape characters. The known types are: \b \f \n \r \t \" \\ ␀* *not atm

        Default: true

      • setAllowExponential

        public void setAllowExponential(boolean key)
        Allow exponential in numeric values. Example: 12E+1, 12e+1, 12e-1, 12e1, etc

        Default: true

      • setAllowUpperCaseValues

        public void setAllowUpperCaseValues(boolean key)
        Allow boolean or null values to be upper-case. Example: FALSE, NULL, TrUe
        Note that this will remove case-sensitivity allowing values with mixed caps.
        This will have no affect to the exponential character (E / e) which will allways be case-insensitive

        Default: true

      • setParseNulls

        public void setParseNulls(boolean key)
        If false, all keys mapped to null are ignored during the parsing, making them disappear from the final JSON string representation.
        If true null values will be parsed into the JSON object
        In both cases calling JSONEntity.get(Object) with a key that maps to a null value will return null, but functions like JSONObject#containsKey will have a different result

        Default: true

      • setParseEscapedAsUnescaped

        public void setParseEscapedAsUnescaped(boolean key)
        If true it will replace escaped characters found in strings (see setAllowUnknownEscapes(boolean) for known escapes list)
        for its unescaped counterpart. I.e: "key1":"whats\\ up" to "key1":"whats\ up"

        Default: true

      • setMaxJsonDepth

        public void setMaxJsonDepth(int key)
        UNIMPLEMENTED. Sets the max number of depth while parsing a json string, this is how deep a json structure is, for example a max depth of 2 will not allow a json inside a json inside a json, since this is considered to have a depth of 3. A max depth of -1 will mean no depth limit, which will cascade into the stack recursivity limit

        Default: -1
